text.section:
To establish the existence of a "criminal gang" as defined in KRS 506.140, any competent evidence that is probative of the existence of or membership in a criminal gang shall be admissible, including the following:
Self-proclamation;
A common name, insignia, flag, or means of recognition;
Common identifying hand or body signs, signals, or code;
A common identifying mode, style, or color of dress;
An identifying tattoo or body marking;
Membership, age, or other qualifications;
Creed of belief;
An organizational or command structure, overt or covert;
A de facto claim of territory or jurisdiction;
An initiation ritual;
A concentration or specialty; or
A method of operation or criminal enterprise.

It is no defense to prosecution under KRS 506.140 that:
One (1) or more members of the gang are not criminally responsible for the offense;
One (1) or more members of the gang have been acquitted, have not been prosecuted or convicted, have been convicted of a different offense, or are under prosecution;
A person has been charged with, acquitted, or convicted of any offense under KRS 506.140;
The participants may not know each other's identity;
The membership in the criminal gang may change from time to time; or
The participants may stand in a wholesaler-retailer or other arm's length arrangement in the conduct of illicit distribution or other operations.
